Submitted by Councillor R. King:
WHEREAS the City of Ottawa continues to experience increasing pressures related to unsheltered homelessness and encampments, with impacts on both individuals and surrounding communities; 
WHEREAS seasonal trends and warmer weather conditions are associated with increased visibility and prevalence of encampments across the city, resulting in a corresponding rise in service requests, community impacts, and the need for timely, coordinated response; 
WHEREAS the City’s encampment response involves multiple departments, partners, and reporting channels, resulting in data that is currently collected but not consistently consolidated or proactively shared with Ward Councillors; 
WHEREAS Ward Councillors have sought regular and timely access to encampment-related data, however historical reporting has been inconsistent, with limited updates provided in recent years, reflecting challenges in sustaining manual reporting processes; 
WHEREAS staff have indicated that the administrative effort required to manually compile and distribute encampment data limits the frequency of reporting and creates ongoing reliance on ad hoc requests; 
WHEREAS staff have incrementally improved access to more timely information through the development of a public-facing reporting dashboard, which would reduce reliance on manual reporting and improve transparency; 
WHEREAS the Unsheltered Homelessness Outreach Model report (ACS2026-CSS-GEN-003) included the development of an integrated data system, improved tracking of encampments, and enhanced public reporting to support coordination, transparency, and data-informed decision-making; 
WHEREAS the City of Ottawa has successfully implemented standardized reporting tools in other service areas, such as building permit activity and Greenhouse gas emissions, to improve accessibility, transparency, and operational awareness for Councillor’s offices; 
WHEREAS timely, accurate, and consolidated information is critical to enabling Ward Councillors to respond effectively to resident concerns, and the use of real-time data systems and emerging technologies, including artificial intelligence, can improve situational awareness, reduce reliance on manual reporting, and support more informed, responsive, and coordinated decision-making, while also enabling Councillors to better communicate with and educate residents and community organizations on encampment response, available supports, and the City’s approach; 
THEREFORE BE IT RESOLVED that Community Services Committee recommend that Council direct the General Manager of Community and Social Services, in collaboration relevant departments, to:
